# Documentation Standards

## README Structure
- **Project Title**: Clear, descriptive title with tagline
- **Why Section**: Explain the problem and solution
- **Key Features**: Bullet points of main capabilities
- **Quickstart**: Step-by-step getting started guide
- **Installation**: Clear installation instructions
- **Usage Examples**: Practical command-line examples
- **Configuration**: Explain configuration options
- **Benchmarks**: Performance results and targets
- **Contributing**: How to contribute to the project

## Code Documentation
- **Docstrings**: Use Google-style docstrings for all public functions
- **Type Hints**: Include type annotations for all parameters
- **Examples**: Provide usage examples in docstrings
- **Equations**: Include mathematical notation for complex operations
- **References**: Cite relevant papers and implementations

## Configuration Documentation
- **YAML Comments**: Explain non-obvious configuration parameters
- **Default Values**: Document all default parameter values
- **Parameter Ranges**: Specify valid ranges for numeric parameters
- **Examples**: Provide sample configurations for common use cases

## CLI Documentation
- **Help Text**: Comprehensive help for all command-line options
- **Examples**: Include practical command-line examples
- **Error Messages**: Clear, actionable error messages
- **Exit Codes**: Document all possible exit codes

## Benchmark Documentation
- **Hardware Specs**: Document test hardware configuration
- **Methodology**: Explain how benchmarks were conducted
- **Reproducibility**: Include exact commands and random seeds
- **Results Table**: Present results in clear, comparable format

## Architecture Documentation
- **Model Diagrams**: Include visual representations when helpful
- **Mathematical Details**: Document key equations and algorithms
- **Implementation Notes**: Explain design decisions and trade-offs
- **Performance Characteristics**: Document expected performance behavior
